What is Traffic Tunnelling?
Traffic tunnelling is the process of encapsulating data inside another protocol so it can pass through networks securely or secretly.
Legitimate Uses: Secure communication between networks, VPNs & Private network access
Malicious Uses: Attackers use tunnelling to bypass firewalls/security tools by hiding data inside trusted protocols like: ICMP & DNS

ICMP Analysis
What is ICMP? Internet Control Message Protocol is mainly used for: Ping, Network troubleshooting & Error reporting
Why Attackers Use ICMP: ICMP packets can carry extra payload data.
Attackers may use it for: Data exfiltration, Command & Control (C2) & Hidden communication channels

Signs of ICMP Tunnelling
Large Number of ICMP Packets
Unexpected high ICMP traffic.

Large Packet Sizes
Normal ping packets are often around 64 bytes.
Large payloads may indicate tunnelling.

Repeated Communication to Same Host
Continuous ICMP requests/replies to one IP.

Hidden Payload Data
Suspicious raw data inside ICMP packets.

DNS Analysis
What is DNS? DNS converts domain names into IP addresses.
Example: google.com → IP Address
Why Attackers Use DNS: DNS is trusted and always allowed in most networks. Attackers hide data in DNS queries.
Common DNS Tunnel Method: Encoded subdomains: ZXhhbXBsZWNvbW1hbmQ=.maliciousdomain.com

The encoded section may contain: Commands, Data & Malware instructions

Signs of DNS Tunnelling
Very Long DNS Queries
Long subdomains are suspicious.

Random Strings
Base64 / encoded text.
Example: a8dh29shd82h2j.example.com

High Volume of Queries to One Domain
Repeated requests to same suspicious domain.

Unusual Query Length

Investigation Workflow
ICMP
Filter ICMP traffic
Check packet sizes
Check repeated destinations
Inspect payload data
Compare normal vs suspicious traffic

DNS
Filter DNS traffic
Check query lengths
Look for random strings
Check repeated domains
Count query frequency

